1.2  Situation – What Was the Problem?
Braintree's Australian merchants were processing Visa and Mastercard transactions through NAB (National Australia Bank) as the acquiring bank and processor. This created a hard dependency on a third-party institution for dispute handling — chargebacks, retrievals, and representments had to be routed through NAB, which added latency, reduced control, and limited our ability to scale the disputes workflow globally.
Fiserv, which already acted as acquirer and processor for Braintree's US EPP (First Data) integration, was expanding its GMA (Global Merchant Acquiring) platform to Australia via its Carat infrastructure. The goal was to migrate AU merchants to Fiserv's GMA platform — eliminating NAB dependency and consolidating our disputes pipeline under a single processor relationship.
The challenge: GMA was a net-new integration. While an EPP Fiserv framework existed in the US, GMA had a meaningfully different Snowflake schema, and the entire end-to-end pipeline — from data ingest through dispute creation to representment — had to be designed for extensibility across future regions (NZ, CA, etc.), not just AU.

1.3  Task – What Was My Ownership?
I authored the RFC end-to-end, which meant I was responsible for:
