•	Researching and evaluating multiple design options for every shared component — S3 structure, ingest runners, FileProcessor/RowProcessor, chargeback/retrieval data models, strategy engines, TransactionFinder, TransactionBuilder, dispute sources, and batch acquirers.
•	Identifying cross-team dependencies and blockers (Fiserv data team, Snowglobe team, Funding team, Gateway team).
•	Driving the Snowflake schema analysis, including SQL-based column diff queries comparing BTAUSTRALIA vs BTFISERV schemas.
•	Collaborating with the SnowGlobe team on the Kafka-based financial event and disbursement protocol for GMA.
•	Defining MVP stories and estimations across all engineering tracks.

1.4  Action – Key Technical Decisions & How I Solved Them
Snowflake Schema Analysis & Column Mapping
The AU Snowflake schema (BTAUSTRALIA) did not match the existing EPP schema (BTFISERV). I wrote SQL queries to do a systematic column diff — identifying 25+ extra columns in the AU chargeback table and 2 missing columns, and a similar analysis for retrievals. This became the foundation for the data mapping spike and unblocked the Terraform/warehouse setup work.

Extensible Architecture for Multi-Region GMA
Rather than building an AU-only solution, I designed the architecture to scale to future GMA regions (NZ, CA). Key decisions:
•	S3 path structure: Region-specific subfolders within a GMA folder to cleanly isolate processor files without fragmenting the existing Fiserv bucket layout.
•	Ingest Runner: Single runner with region-aware S3 path parameterization over individual runners per region.
•	Data Models: Recommended STI (Single Table Inheritance) — single table maintains query simplicity, while region-specific child classes handle divergent logic.
•	ProcessorFileService: Nested PROCESSOR_TO_SOURCE map to cleanly route AU, NZ, and CA to their respective Dispute::Source constants.
•	TransactionFinder: Single finder class + single transaction_details table with a region column — avoiding redundant tables.

SnowGlobe Financial Integration
GMA introduced a new financial flow where SnowGlobe (rather than Funding) would be responsible for fee calculation and disbursement. I led the Q&A with the SnowGlobe team and established that Arbiter would publish to the same Kafka topic, SnowGlobe would consume and publish disbursement events back on the existing topic, and no message contract changes were required. This de-risked the integration significantly.

Representment via SFTP
The existing EPP representment pipeline was reusable in large part. The key delta was identifying the GMA-specific SFTP configuration and creating a new GMA::AU SFTP client and batch acquirer. I mapped exactly which components needed new classes vs. simple factory mappings.

