4. ProcessorFileService
It's an important decision the way we are choosing sources so in the future we have a separate source for different operations (aggregation for stats collection, differentiating PREs, funding use source for the disputes). We can configure the base source as GMA and then segregate them based on regions.

PROCESSOR_TO_SOURCE = {
  gma: {
    au: Dispute::Source::FISERV_AU,
    nz: Dispute::Source::FISERV_NZ,
    ca: Dispute::Source::FISERV_CA
  }
}

@file_service = ProcessorFileService.new(
  contents: file_content,
  filename: filepath.split("/").last,
  processor: :gma,
  file_type: processor_file_type,
  region: :au  # may be, not sure
)

def source(processor, region)
  if processor == :gma
    region_sources = PROCESSOR_TO_SOURCE[processor]
    region_sources[region]
  else
    PROCESSOR_TO_SOURCE[processor]
  end
end

5. Chargebacks / Retrievals
Using the existing models and tables
Assumption: Fiserv would send normalized processor record attributes consistent across regions without much divergent behavior. Also, the relevant columns for validations on the models will remain the same, otherwise we need to validate columns based on region.
Risk: While method branching provides some customization, it might not be enough for regions that diverge significantly from the base model. This could lead to code clarity and maintenance problems.

Changes required if using existing models:
•	Modify the existing Fiserv chargeback and retrieval classes to accommodate region tracking by introducing a new 'region' column. This requires backfilling for all existing EPP records.
•	Implement method branching in Chargeback and Retrieval model classes to handle region-specific functionalities.
•	Capacity estimation for chargeback and retrieval tables to handle increased load from multiple regions.

Creating new models and tables — let's think of EPP as Fiserv version-0 and we won't add complexities to it. We would build a Fiserv/GMA version-1 developed for extensibility across regions.

OPTION 1: Single Table for GMA + Single Chargeback Class for GMA + Protocol
✓ Pros	✗ Cons
Easy to implement initially due to a single class.	Integrating new regions with diverging features could become cumbersome with conditional logic.
Simplest model in terms of database maintenance.	May not scale well — all data in a single table can lead to slower query performance.
	Polymorphic association might be difficult to implement.
	If relevant data columns change, the table would end up with too many NULL columns.
	Complex to use different strategy sets for region-specific requirements.

Pseudocode:
class GmaChargeback < ActiveRecord::Base
  self.table_name = 'gma_chargebacks'
  # all the logic for different gma regions
  conform_to ProcessorRecordProtocol
end

OPTION 2: Multiple Tables for Each GMA Chargeback + Multiple Individual Classes + Protocol
✓ Pros	✗ Cons
Provides adaptability — each region's specific logic is encapsulated in its dedicated class and table.	More tables and classes to manage — increased maintenance overhead.
Isolation simplifies handling regional behavior.	Duplicate code if region-specific behavior is identical.

Pseudocode:
class GmaChargebackAU < ActiveRecord::Base
  self.table_name = 'gma_chargebacks_au'
  # specific processing logic for AU
  conform_to ProcessorRecordProtocol
end

class GmaChargebackNZ < ActiveRecord::Base
  self.table_name = 'gma_chargebacks_nz'
  # specific processing logic for NZ
  conform_to ProcessorRecordProtocol
end

OPTION 3: Single Table + STI (Single Table Inheritance) with Base Class and Individual Child Classes + Protocol
✓ Pros	✗ Cons
Managing a single table simplifies database maintenance.	May not scale well — all data in a single table can lead to slower query performance.
With STI, retrieving and working with data across different regions can be handled separately.	If relevant data columns keep changing, we would end up with null values in many columns.
Each region-specific class can handle its custom functionality.	If class-specific logic doesn't branch out much, we'd have redundant classes.

Pseudocode:
class CreateGmaChargebacks < ActiveRecord::Migration[6.0]
  def up
    create_table :gma_chargebacks do |t|
      t.string :type  # Important for STI
      t.string :region
    end
  end
end

class GmaChargeback < ActiveRecord::Base
  REGION_TO_CLASS = {
    'AU' => 'GmaChargebackAU',
    'US' => 'GmaChargebackUS',
  }

  def self.class_for_region(region_code)
    const_get(REGION_TO_CLASS[region_code])
  end
end

class ChargebackAu < GmaChargeback
  # Automatically uses the 'gma_chargebacks' table
end

chargeback_class = GmaChargeback.class_for_region(processor_record[:region])
chargeback_class.new(build_attributes(processor_record))
chargeback_class.save!

OPTION 4: Multiple Table + Inheritance Model with Abstract Base Class and Individual Child Classes + Protocol
✓ Pros	✗ Cons
Each region-specific subclass can have a database table tailored to its needs.	Managing multiple tables and classes increases complexity and maintenance overhead.
Changes in one region's subclass do not affect others — separation of concerns.	
Each table can be scaled independently.	

OPTION 5: Polymorphic Relations
✓ Pros	✗ Cons
Each region would have specific tables representing specific details. Easily extensible.	Assumes the common table never changes — if it does, breaking apart would be incredibly difficult.
Prevents duplicative columns across tables.	Having association IDs live on the 'common' table is a database anti-pattern — the details don't have a foreign key pointing to the 'common' table.

6. Strategies
We may encounter situations where the structure or sequence of records varies by region. Additionally, certain criteria within a strategy might be relevant for one region but not others. We must either adapt strategies by branching on region or develop entirely new strategies specific to each region.

OPTION 1: Using Existing Strategies + Creating New Ones as Needed
✓ Pros	✗ Cons
Leverages established and proven strategies.	Strategy namespace can become cluttered and confusing if some exist in Fiserv namespace while others exist in region-specific namespaces.
Reduced development time and minimized introduction of new bugs.	Difficult to implement and maintain if we have a single chargeback class for GMA — need to implement multiple sources within the same class.
New strategies can be developed specifically for regional variations.	

